## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

This code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort()` kills a thread that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006). The fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### What's wrong with the original code on .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if the delegate itself doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If your `work` delegate is long-running, accept a token

The above unblocks the *caller* on timeout, but the delegate keeps running in the background until it finishes. To actually **stop the work**, pass the token into it:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work doesn't check the token** | Cancellation is *cooperative* — unlike `Thread.Abort`, it won't interrupt a running CPU-bound loop. Add `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous socket reads, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` or async I/O overloads. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` ≠ stopping the task** | `WaitAsync` only unblocks the caller — the abandoned task still runs. If the work *must* stop, it must check the token. For truly uncooperative code, isolate it in a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`. |

### Async version (preferred if your call site can be async)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

This is the cleanest path on .NET 8 — fully async, no thread pool blocking, and the token flows end-to-end.
